<span class=dateline>September 12, 2003</span> - Alan VanCouvering is back for the second and final Lost Dungeons of Norrath bi-weekly Q&A. Starting in two weeks, we will move to a general EverQuest Q&A. You can continue to send me your questions at <A HREF="mailto:lepidus@vaultnetwork.com">lepidus@vaultnetwork.com</A>.<BR>
<BR>
You can <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=56278823&replies=0">comment on this article</A> over on the <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/board.asp?brd=5001">EQ General Board</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> What aspect of Lost Dungeons of Norrath that has not been greatly covered do you find the most impressive?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> I can't really think of any areas that haven't been greatly covered. :)<BR>
<BR>
Considering that this is the day after launch, I'd have to say that right now I'm most impressed with the way launch day went.  Servers came up on time, there were no large files to download (at least if you pre-downloaded over the last several weeks) and folks were in and playing without any issues.<BR>
<BR>
I'm also very pleased by the responses we've seen.  Folks are really enjoying this expansion.  There's a bit of a glow around the office as the team reads the message boards.  We're all very encouraged by the response.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> In my recent tour of one of the new Lost Dungeons of Norrath dungeons, I found very impressive visuals and storyline, but it also seemed as if the monsters were often the same ones over and over. What steps will you take to prevent repetitive dungeons, while still sticking to a theme?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> Well, your tour, if I remember correctly, only took you into a single adventure in one theme.  You only got to see one dungeon in that theme.  Each map in each theme has unique points of interest that are exclusive to that map.  Also, several of the themes have sub-themes, each having a different feel and style within that theme.  For example, Mistmoore's Catacombs has a rough, cave area with lots of creepy spiders, rats, bats, vampires, werewolves and other such creatures.  It also has an intermediate area where the caves become more refined.  There are still rats and such, but the vampires become less feral and other creatures begin to be more common, such as mummies.  Then there are the catacombs closest to the castle itself, with a sophisticated feel, comfy furniture and paintings.<BR>
<BR>
So while you only got to see one of the dungeons, each theme has a pretty broad range of interiors and some variety of NPCs.  When you head into, for example, Cazic-Thule, you don't get anywhere near the variety of scenery and NPCs that you get when you take on an adventure in any of the five themes of the Lost Dungeons.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> Another feature you spoke of was buying items through your adventure points. Could you expand on this feature a little more?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Alan VanCouvering:</B> Sure.  Every time a character completes an adventure they are awarded points.  Even completing the adventure after the timer expires will earn the character a lesser number of points.  These points can be spent at the Wayfarers Brotherhood merchants.  The Brotherhood is a band of adventurers, and they have collected come truly unique items in their travels.  They will sell these to folks that have earned them (represented by the points earned during adventures).  Anything from spells to augmentations and charms can be purchased from these vendors.<div class=byline>-- <a href="mailto:lepidus@vaultnetwork.com">Lepidus</A></div>
